¹ Nomen familiae renovatum] Nomen quod comparaverat sibi Ma- sinissae—M.

³ Per reynifidem] Literally is, by the honour of royalty, i. e. by the honour which a king ought to have. Cortius comments upon it thus, Per fidem quam in regnum acceptus debes—M.

⁴ Concordia ματ-τας res crescunt, &c.] The conduct of Scilurus is an excellent commentary upon this. He had twenty-four sons, or, as some say eighty; and, on his death-bed, in their presence, called for a sheaf of arrows of the same number, and desired each of them to tryto break them, which none of them could do 3 he then took them one by one, and broke them all to pieces before them—designing thereby to teach them that unanimity would be their strength and secunty-and that by division they would be weakened‚ and rendered an easy prey to enemies.-M.
